# Getting Started with Amplitude Java SDK

## Installation

1. Add the Amplitude Java SDK dependency to your project:

   **Maven:**
   ```xml
   <dependency>
     <groupId>com.amplitude</groupId>
     <artifactId>analytics-java</artifactId>
     <version>1.10.0</version>
   </dependency>
   ```

   **Gradle:**
   ```groovy
   implementation 'com.amplitude:analytics-java:1.10.0'
   ```

## Basic Setup and Initialization

1. Import the necessary classes:
   ```java
   import com.amplitude.Amplitude;
   import com.amplitude.Event;
   ```

2. Initialize the SDK with your API key:
   ```java
   Amplitude amplitude = Amplitude.getInstance();
   amplitude.init("YOUR_API_KEY");
   ```

3. Configure the SDK (optional):
   ```java
   // Enable batch mode to optimize network usage
   amplitude.setUseBatchMode(true);
   
   // Set the number of events to batch before sending
   amplitude.setEventUploadThreshold(50);
   
   // Set the maximum time between batch uploads (in milliseconds)
   amplitude.setEventUploadPeriodMillis(10000);
   ```

## Tracking Events

### Track a Simple Event

```java
// Create and log a basic event
amplitude.logEvent(new Event("Button Clicked", "user_123"));
```

### Track an Event with Properties

```java
// Create an event with properties
Event event = new Event("Product Purchased", "user_123");
event.eventProperties.put("product_id", "SKU-123");
event.eventProperties.put("price", 99.99);
event.eventProperties.put("currency", "USD");

// Log the event
amplitude.logEvent(event);
```

### Set User Properties

```java
// Import the Identify class
import com.amplitude.Identify;

// Create an identify object
Identify identify = new Identify()
    .set("email", "user@example.com")
    .set("plan_type", "premium")
    .setOnce("initial_signup_date", "2023-01-15");

// Associate these properties with a user
amplitude.identify("user_123", identify);
```

## Ensuring Events Are Sent

By default, events are batched and sent automatically based on your configuration. To manually flush events:

```java
// Force immediate upload of all queued events
amplitude.flushEvents();
```

## Complete Example

```java
import com.amplitude.Amplitude;
import com.amplitude.Event;
import com.amplitude.Identify;

public class AmplitudeExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Initialize SDK
        Amplitude amplitude = Amplitude.getInstance();
        amplitude.init("YOUR_API_KEY");
        
        // Configure batch settings
        amplitude.setUseBatchMode(true);
        amplitude.setEventUploadThreshold(50);
        amplitude.setEventUploadPeriodMillis(10000);
        
        // Set user properties
        Identify identify = new Identify()
            .set("email", "user@example.com")
            .set("account_type", "business");
        amplitude.identify("user_123", identify);
        
        // Track a simple event
        Event event = new Event("Login Successful", "user_123");
        event.eventProperties.put("login_method", "email");
        event.eventProperties.put("app_version", "2.1.3");
        
        amplitude.logEvent(event);
        
        // Ensure events are sent before application exits
        amplitude.flushEvents();
    }
}
```

This basic implementation will get you started with tracking events in your Java application using the Amplitude Java SDK.